<LG>
<L>To name great WILLIAM, Briton's noble&s;t boa&s;t,</L>
<L>And how he drubb'd guid CHARLEY with his ho&s;t,</L>
<L>Not half &s;o galls our Caledonian friends,</L>
<L>As he who blames a B&mdash;T&mdash;, or W&mdash;K-S commends.</L>
<L>B&mdash;T-'s all perfection, SCOTLAND's only brave,</L>
<L>ENGLISH are gluttons, and their W&mdash;K-S a knave:</L>
<L>Are the fal&s;e themes, each Scotti&s;h dunce repeats,</L>
<L>Who drinks to CHARLEY, often as he eats.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="17" REF="010112_0018_0F7CE9FBBA9204C0">
<L>Hear how two Loons! their Chieftains worth extol'd,</L>
<L>And loud his prai&s;e in &s;ick'ning raptures ball'd,</L>
<L>Sowens and Whi&s;key, all their mirth awoke,</L>
<L>And for their favour'd B&mdash;TE, thus SAWNEY &s;poke;</L>
<L>"Deil take me DONALD, bat he's unco guid,</L>
<L>"And foal'd <NOTE N="(i)" PLACE="foot">As our author has given a &s;pecimen of the Scotch dialect, a tran&s;lation of a few of the mo&s;t material words, might not be ami&s;s, <HI>e. g.</HI> Foal'd&mdash;Born.</NOTE> my friend frae be&s;t o' HIGHLAND bluid <NOTE N="(k)" PLACE="foot">Bluid&mdash;Blood.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Frae NORTH to SOUTH, there's nane in a' the land,</L>
<L>"Before this doughty L&mdash;D, for bluid can &s;tand,</L>
<L>"He was na' foal'd, as a' the ENGLISH crew,</L>
<L>"Kings &s;prang frae him, as bearns <NOTE N="(l)" PLACE="foot">Bearns&mdash;Children.</NOTE> frae me an' you.</L>
<L>"Saul man! I'd &s;pang, with muckle glee I'd &s;ing,</L>
<L>"If but bra' CHARLEY was the BRITISH king.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>"Haud Chiel! (&s;ays DONALD) troth! ye are nae blate <NOTE N="(m)" PLACE="foot">Blate&mdash;Clever or genteel.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Wat <NOTE N="(n)" PLACE="foot">Wat&mdash;Know.</NOTE> ye no' well? wha's M&mdash;ST-R o' ST-TE&punc;</L>
<L>"Is it no' B&mdash;T? tho' G&mdash;V&mdash; has the name,</L>
<L>"G&mdash;V&mdash;, a creature o' nae muckle fame;</L>
<L>"B-T- gives us places, pen&s;ions at the C&mdash;T,</L>
<L>"And &s;corns the Engli&s;h, for his ane dear &s;port;</L>
<L>"A hantle &s;iller <NOTE N="(o)" PLACE="foot">Hantle &s;iller&mdash;Much, or a great deal of money.</NOTE> has our Laddies made,</L>
<L>"Oh! this C&mdash;T traffick, is a ble&s;&s;ed trade!</L>
<L>"Was the GUID PRINCE, to govern BRITONS T&mdash;,</L>
<L>"He could nae mair <NOTE N="(p)" PLACE="foot">Mair&mdash;More.</NOTE> do, than L&mdash; B-T- has done;</L>
<L>"Ye ken fu' weel, a ST&mdash;T canno reign,</L>
<L>"Ah dreadfu' thought! it gees me unco pain;</L>
<L>"Bat ST&mdash;TS can be M-N ST-RS o' &s;tate,</L>
<L>"Tho' England loath them, wi' the muck'le&s;t hate;</L>
<L>"Thus our guid L&mdash;D, God ble&s;s his noble &s;oul,</L>
<L>"Makes goud in goupings <NOTE N="(q)" PLACE="foot">Goud in goupins&mdash;Gold in handfulls.</NOTE> to us Scotchmen roal;</L>
<L><PB N="18" REF="010112_0019_0F7CE9FC9A211A28">"Lat you an' I friend SAWNEY, gang to town,</L>
<L>"An' &s;peer <NOTE N="(r)" PLACE="foot">Speer&mdash;A&s;k.</NOTE> o' the bra' L&mdash;D, &s;ome feckle&s;s <NOTE N="(&s;)" PLACE="foot">Feekle&s;s&mdash;Trifling, or &s;mall.</NOTE> boon,</L>
<L>"Enough o' places he has geen our lads,</L>
<L>"Perhaps for me an' you, &s;ome po&s;t he hades."</L>
<L>"Wi' a' my &s;aul, (cries SAWNEY,) lat us gang,</L>
<L>"Lat's bu&s;s our bearns, an' down to LONDON &s;pang."</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The&s;e NORTHERN BRITONS, greatly I commend,</L>
<L>To wealth as others, all their actions tend:</L>
<L>They would be ba&s;ely mean, they'd act the brute,</L>
<L>Not to a&s;cribe all virtues to their B-TE;</L>
<L>When from his partial hand, they &s;hare all good,</L>
<L>Becau&s;e ally'd by Caledonian blood.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Sure none can blame them! to accept a place,</L>
<L>When &s;olely proffer'd to their kindred race.</L>
<L>They're poor, they're proud, but ENGLAND knows they're BRAVE,</L>
<L>Witne&s;s each war, and how they've fed the grave.</L>
<L>In friend&s;hip they're &s;incere, in honour ju&s;t,</L>
<L>They love a &s;tation, and they love a tru&s;t:</L>
<L>But to one center, like the Jews they move,</L>
<L>Their greate&s;t crime, is a too partial love:</L>
<L>It is an inbred pa&s;&s;ion, SCOTLAND feeds,</L>
<L>From a too narrow mind the fault proceeds.</L>
<L>Thus they love B-T-, and B-T- he loves a SCOT,</L>
<L>Hence ev'ry profit is their nation's lot.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>B&mdash; is the man we only &s;hould dete&s;t, <NOTE N="(t)" PLACE="foot">Differing from the mo&s;t of my countrymen, in point of politicks, I can't help joining with the author, that we &s;hould trace party differences to their &s;ource, nor attribute the political compo|&s;itions of a W&mdash;s as the only cau&s;e. W&mdash;s could never have found fault, (as he has done) had there not been too ju&s;t rea&s;on for it, both from mal-adm&mdash;&s;t&mdash;n, and partial be&s;towment of favours: by which only, has that friendly UNION, &s;ub&s;i&s;ting between two N-TIONS been greatly marr'd.</NOTE></L>
<L>As UNIONS foe, as ENGLAND's greate&s;t pe&s;t;</L>
<L><PB N="19" REF="010112_0020_0F7CE9FD34C454D0">Before his horrid, dark, and gloomy reign,</L>
<L>The &s;ouls of SCOTCH and ENGLISH were the &s;ame,</L>
<L>One general love pre&s;ided through the land,</L>
<L>All like good brothers, gave to all their hand;</L>
<L>No party words, nor &s;cornful taunts were us'd,</L>
<L>None for his COUNTRY, or his TONGUE abus'd;</L>
<L>But now! oh &s;trange! how alter'd, how unju&s;t!</L>
<L>A nation, for the crime of one is curs'd.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Blame B&mdash; ye Britons, don't de&s;pi&s;e that land,</L>
<L>Becau&s;e they take what's offer'd to their hand:</L>
<L>On him alone, if cur&s;es you mu&s;t pour,</L>
<L>Let loo&s;e your vengeance, and exhau&s;t its &s;tore;</L>
<L>Bid injur'd peace, its outmo&s;t fury &s;hed,</L>
<L>And fall as pond'rous ruin on his head;</L>
<L>Bid haggar'd con&s;cience, treat him as her foe,</L>
<L>And like the rolling &s;tone <NOTE N="(u)" PLACE="foot">This is in allu&s;ion, (according to the Grecian mythology) to the puni&s;hment of Si&s;iphus in Hell.&mdash;Who is &s;aid by &s;ome, to have been a Trojan &s;ecretary, and thus puni&s;hed for certain crimes of &s;tate.</NOTE>, give con&s;tant woe;</L>
<L>Bid ju&s;tice mark him, as it marks a knave,</L>
<L>And deep repentance, bow him to the grave;</L>
<L>Till then, and only then, will England re&s;t,</L>
<L>So deep the rancour in each Engli&s;h brea&s;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>For me, I cou'd not wi&s;h him a wor&s;e fate,</L>
<L>Than galling con&s;cience, and his ma&s;ter's hate.</L>
<L>The R&mdash;L ear, he greatly has abus'd,</L>
<L>For &s;elfi&s;h ends the R&mdash;L name has us'd;</L>
<L>Thus has e&s;trang'd, his &s;ubjects from their ****,</L>
<L>That few ala&s;s! too few, his prai&s;es &s;ing.</L>
<L>Where are the &s;houts, that wont to rend the &s;ky,</L>
<L>And where the joy, that gleam'd from ev'ry eye,</L>
<L>At &s;ight of him, what acclamations rung,</L>
<L>Long live our ****, was echo'd from each tongue;</L>
<L>But now, unheeded may he pa&s;s along,</L>
<L>And &s;carce a wi&s;h, is whi&s;per'd by the throng.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="20" REF="010112_0021_0F7CE9FDFAE51278">
<L>Whence comes this coolne&s;s in each Engli&s;h brea&s;t,</L>
<L>The Engli&s;h are de&s;pis'd, the Scotch care&s;s'd;</L>
<L>Their country feels, a tax-de&s;troying wa&s;te,</L>
<L>While Schotchmen have, each profit and each po&s;t,</L>
<L>At HOME, ABROAD, C&mdash;, ARMY, and the FLEET,</L>
<L>You MC and MC in endle&s;s numbers meet;</L>
<L>While England's &s;ons, as true and brave as they,</L>
<L>Are &s;carce in office, pen&s;ion, po&s;t, or pay.</L>
<L>Hence all this coolne&s;s, hence the darling hi&s;s,</L>
<L>And all th' affronts, a **** mu&s;t take ami&s;s.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Th' unhappy man! I pity from my heart,</L>
<L>That can't di&s;tingui&s;h, foes from friends apart,</L>
<L>That's clo&s;e encompa&s;s'd, by a flatt'ring crew,</L>
<L>Of ba&s;e di&s;&s;embler's, of the blacke&s;t hue,</L>
<L>Who prate of virtues, which none ever had,</L>
<L>And call that plea&s;ing, which the world calls &s;ad&punc;</L>
<L>Fellows! that round in cringing order wait,</L>
<L>Meer &s;ervile dupes, to pageantry and &s;tate,</L>
<L>"Who&s;e greate&s;t merit lies in doing ill,</L>
<L>"In con&s;tant changing, and in erring &s;till."</L>
<L>Such round our K&mdash;, like Stygeon demons &s;tand,</L>
<L>A flatt'ring, crafty, fawning, trait'rous band;</L>
<L>Who bar all acce&s;s, to the R&mdash; ear,</L>
<L>Nor whi&s;per what a gracious K&mdash; &s;hould hear;</L>
<L>Creatures! that follow fairy-fancy'd dreams,</L>
<L>And turn the wheels of &s;tate, with idle &s;chemes;</L>
<L>Meer abject blockheads, in the &s;cale of worth,</L>
<L>Yet bent on novelty, incompa&s;s earth,</L>
<L>And ruin countries, for a mou&s;e's birth. <NOTE N="(w)" PLACE="foot">This line &s;eems to have a reference to the impolitical and tyrannous proceedings of the M&mdash;T-Y; and the trifle the N-T-N mu&s;t receive from the C-L-N&mdash;S, amid&s;t all the arbitrary, ruinous, and oppre&s;&s;ive methods they are taking; in regard to the ST-MP DUTEIS T-XES, &amp;c. &amp;c.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Such mighty nothings, from my &s;oul I hate,</L>
<L>And &s;o de&s;pi&s;e them, as the banes of &s;tate:</L>
<L>Nor would I change my happy &s;phere of life,</L>
<L>For all the folly of a c&mdash;r<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 letter">ly &s;trife:</L>
<L><PB N="21" REF="010112_0022_0F7CE9FF32540498">My country's cau&s;e, has &s;olely urg'd my &s;ong,</L>
<L>And made me mingle with the &s;cribbling throng:</L>
<L>El&s;e I'd ne'er ventur'd, "on a &s;ea of rhime,"</L>
<L>The critics la&s;h, and "perils of the time."</L>
<L>I envy none the favour of the C****,</L>
<L>While B&mdash; makes G&mdash;L truckle for his &s;port:</L>
<L>Pull but the lawrel, from that tyrant's brow,</L>
<L>Send him to SCOTLAND, G&mdash;L to his plow:</L>
<L>Make S&mdash;D&mdash;H, M&mdash;LD, each re&s;ign their po&s;t,</L>
<L>And roaring N&mdash;T&mdash;N, &s;camper with the re&s;t;</L>
<L>Then will I cea&s;e; then high Heaven adore</L>
<L>That fal&s;hood, pride, oppre&s;&s;ion, are no more.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
